How and when is it appropriate to push back or tell your manager they are wrong without damaging the working relationship? How can regular check-ins or periodic one-on-one meetings create a space to address concerns early, clarify expectations, and prevent larger conflicts from building up over time? In what ways can strategies like reflective listening during these check-ins make it easier to raise disagreements, and how can an employee use these moments to distinguish between a manager’s misunderstanding versus poor judgment? At what point does pushing back become necessary, even if it risks tension in the relationship?
